I’m excited to see my work paired with Elo Wobig's plein air paintings @elowobig and Robbie McClaren's black and white photography @robbiemcclaran.  The theme for our show is "Inner Landscapes" and for me the emphasis is definitely on the "inner." I'll have 17 pieces in the show.  Some inspired by the colors and marks of nature, others by the urban landscape.

Opening night is Tues. Dec. 6 and will be launched with a pop-up vendor show of 46 artists and craftspeople from 5-8 pm.  I’ll have some small pieces available at very special pop-up prices that night.  Hope you can make it by!

The show will run through Jan. 20 at Walters Art Center.  527 E Main St.  Hillsboro, OR.

As I’m lost in a sea of neutral colors trying to decide on new carpeting, I’m very thankful I’ve spent so much time studying their nuances!  I can usually spot the undertones of green or pink, leanings of gray or brown.  But my fingers are still crossed that the tiny samples I look at will look the same once they fill a whole room.

This was such a fun project and so great to see the final results!  I was grouped with @elowobig and @robbiemcclaran  We were given the show title of “Inner Landscapes” and encouraged to explore it in whatever way we wanted. 

My pieces used landscape (or urbanscape) as inspiration for colors, shapes, and textures. Some aim at capturing the feeling of place with drama or quiet spaces.  Others are inspired by the signs, graffiti and peeling posters on city walls. 

It was so great to see our show hanging for the first time!  We all work in such different styles that I wasn’t sure how it would all come together. Thanks to Karl Leclair @leclair_k director at Walters Art Center for his very sensitive groupings. 

The show is at Walters Art Center in Hillsboro, OR through Jan. 20.

I’m exhausted!  I went from having a show opening to a flight to CA the next day to help my mom move into assisted living.  Now I’m doing nothing for quite a while.  I was so happy to see this new Winter Bash from @winslowartcenter just in time to allow me to sit around, drink tea, and watch art demos.  I’ve enjoyed many of their offerings in the past.  They lean towards representational art, but it’s always interesting to watch other artists work and gather tips from them.  They are free, but you do need to register to receive the Zoom link.

I love this time of year for reflecting and pondering my next direction. Going through my work, I find these 3 pop out at me right now.  They are not necessarily favorites, but they seem to have some juice in them for me, and I’m trying to figure out what they have in common.

1.  They all have color combinations that surprise me.
2.  They all have a strong structure to them, yet plenty that remains out of control.
3.  They all hint at something representational while remaining largely abstract. 
4.  They all contain some amount of prominent drawing.

I think I’ll play with those 4 elements and see where they lead me.

.
.
.
.
.
.

I’m still working on starting paintings in three different ways to see where each leads. For this one, I’ve been building up lots of layers of transparent marks. 

I wanted some dark so am now going in with a pthalo blue mix. I first applied it almost dry leaving canvas breaking through. Scraped through the thicker areas to allow areas of light to add some depth to the marks. I then added medium to it for more transparent marks. Finally went in with a damp paper towel for thin smearing. 

I’m curious to see how long I can build up transparency before I’m called to go thicker.  Or maybe I’ll decide I like a whole painting built solely of layers of transparency. I’ve never done one of those before.  Have you?

Day 3-  Work in progress

After taking much of Dec. off, I’m just trying to loosen up again and get back to painting.  I have a note up in my studio that says "Visual Morning Pages" as a reminder to treat the paintings exactly as I do my writing. 

I’ve been doing Morning Pages for probably 25 years now and can’t start my day without them. They are a total brain dump of freestyle writing on the page. No editing. No pausing to judge. Just clearing the brain. That’s how I want to start my paintings. Later I’ll come in and start making adjustments and shaping them, quieting some things down and intensifying others, but right now, it’s about getting the flow going. 
.
.
.

Day 5- Favorite Tool

I suppose these would be the one thing I would take to a desert island.  I love everything about these Blackwing pencils.  They are smooth and dark.  They hold a nice sharp point.  The flattened eraser is the perfect shape for cleaning up edges. And I especially love that they are white.  I can always spot them easily in my sea of black pencils.

Day 6– Current challenge

I’ve been experimenting with ways of combining painting and hand stitching.  I love the combo of the fast, loose paint and the slower movement of the hand stitching. The problem is if I paint thick and juicy with acrylic paint it’s very hard to stitch through.  Also if I work on thinner paper to make stitching easier, it can end up too puckery. 

I was happy with this piece where I didn’t apply the paint so thickly on the side that would be stitched. But lots of fails on other pieces right now as I try to figure out which approach will work. 
.

Day 7 - Color palette

Maybe 10 years ago, I challenged members in my art group to create a color wheel showing their personal favorite versions of each color.  It was so interesting to see the range from bright primaries, to soft pastels or deep earthy colors, and sometimes a mix of all of them. 

I found my color wheel the other day and thought it would be fun to update it to see if I changed much.  My palette, while still favoring deep colors and dark values, has gotten more muted over the years.  And for certain colors that I struggle with (purple and green), I like heavily grayed down versions.  I realized I hardly ever use straight red, but I do like a barely there pink.  It was fun to compare them and also notice how they’ve played out in my art.  Picture 1. Current.  2. 10ish years ago.  3.  Side by side. 

Have your color preferences changed over the years?

Day 8- Inspiration

I’m always inspired by my daily walks. I live 10 mins. from a fern forest in one direction, and 10 mins. to downtown Portland in the other, so both nature and urban life inspire me. 

I’m especially thrilled when the two worlds collide. I love seeing beautiful bits of nature set off by pavement or concrete. It’s that blending of the pretty and the gritty, and elements that surprise us into taking notice that I’m always after in my work.

Day 9 - Where Art Happens

My studio is in the daylight basement of our home.  Sometimes I dream of a huge separate space away from home, but I do really enjoy the convenience of coming downstairs whenever the mood hits me.  A few things I love in it— my large painting wall with a grid of screws to easily move paintings to any height, some empty flat surfaces to work on (although they never stay empty for long), a clothes drying rack for hanging stained or printed tissue paper for collage, and my cork floors. They are pretty battered after 20 years, but still have a nice amount of cushion for standing all day. And my favorite piece of all is the red vintage toolbox that belonged to my father and is now loaded with art supplies.

Day 13 - Process Insights

It’s so hard to talk about process when most every painting is different. Intentionally so. I like to keep surprising myself with fresh approaches and just see where the painting takes me. 

I do though often tend to start with markmaking or writing on the canvas as a way of getting it started.  Usually not many of those initial marks remain at the end, but occasionally I feature them.

Day 15 - How I name my paintings

I love to collect words and phrases and keep big ongoing lists of them.  They come from songs, poems, books, conversations, or things that just fall out of my head.  Sometimes I brainstorm around a particular theme, such as "ease." I also like to check wordhippo.com to add to the list after I’ve run out of ideas. 

I love it when a painting names itself while I’m working on it. But when that doesn’t happen, I turn to my lists to mix and match.

Day 16- Smallest work

I seldom work smaller than 12x12”, but I do like to do little mini paintings in my sketchbook.  Whenever I test a palette, I like to do a little 5x4” painting next to it using those limited colors. Seeing the colors interact in a piece gives such a different look than just seeing them in a grid..

Day 17 - Largest painting 

My comfort zone seems to stop at about 36”. After that I move to diptychs and triptychs. I find them easier to move around the studio, and I enjoy having the flexibility of turning them in different positions, letting them stand alone or interact. 

The first piece here is my largest - a diptych measuring 40x80” and the second a triptych measuring 24x72”.

I’m celebrating the end of my show with @elowobig and @robbiemcclaran at Walters Art Center in Hillsboro, OR. Day 19 - From the archives

I am a really big fan of daily projects!  I like to take a subject and work with it over and over to see where it will take me. In the past I’ve done the 100 day project with mini collages. I’ve done 100 small black and white composition studies. And I’ve done a year of daily stitched pieces that were then joined together to represent the shifting of the year. 

There’s so much to learn from feeling like you’ve reached the end of creativity and then finding a whole new level of ideas.  Some of my favorite pieces in the series happen at the beginning, but then other favorites can happen at #90 and be full of surprises. And I love a stack of little related pieces when I’m done!

Day 20 - Favorite technique

That’s hard to say since there are so many of them.  I think in general I love to find order in the middle of chaos.  As much as I love to play with layers and markmaking, I think my favorite part is coming back in and quieting them down.  That usually involves applying smooth layers of paint to counteract the color and texture.  For those I like to work flat and use a trowel or flexible broad knife to smooth on large, quiet areas.  Then scrape back in to add subtle interest to them.

Day 21 - Big Dream

One of my favorite trips was a too quick tour of Japan with my sister. I adored the beauty and the oddity around every corner!  It is a land of contrasts with peaceful, traditional beauty next to garish popular culture, and it thrilled me. A friend of mine did a tour of Japan with a focus on the arts and crafts.  My big dream is to do something similar and have more time to absorb the culture. 

Have you done an art tour anywhere that you would recommend?  I did a fabulous private one with friends in Oaxaca, and it’s such a wonderful way to see inside art and craft studios that I might not otherwise get to see.  Eager to do more!

Oh have I been going down a rabbit hole since my friend @cindyswoods introduced me to this book "The Creative Act: A Way of Being" by Rick Rubin.  It’s a fabulous book that someone described as a cross between The Artist's Way and the Tao te Ching, a very apt description. Rick is a music producer who is known to bring out the best in the many diverse artists he works with from the Beastie Boys to The Red Hot Chili Peppers, Johnny Cash and Adele.  He joins observations of how artists create with his sense of the mystery and spiritual connection that underlie the process.

The book got me tracking down all the recent podcasts he’s been on. I think I’ve listened to 6 now, and each one is full of unique stories and insights.  Usually when authors go on the podcast circuit, they seem to repeat the same material.  I don’t know if these podcasters have special gifts at drawing unique things out of the guest or if it's Rick's ability to speak from the present moment, but each of these podcasts has been hugely interesting to me.  Rich Roll, Tim Ferriss, Lex Fridman, Andrew Hubermann, Joe Rogan, Malcolm Gladwell.  Take your pick!  #artinspiration

Emily has you move beyond sight to activate all your senses and gets you to respond deeply to the subject matter in a fresh way.

I’m a moody artist. Sometimes I want to work on a big painting with wild brushstrokes. Other times I want a quiet stitching project.  Last year I learned that by having two very different projects going at once, my loose abstracts and my more controlled geometric circles, I got a lot more done because I could switch projects based on my mood and energy level.

This year I’m taking that idea even further by working with art mood cards I created.  There’s now something for any mood whether it's exuberant large painting or doing a little art history research.

You can find more details about how and why I’m using the art mood cards in my latest blog post.  Link in profile.  And if you would enjoy receiving my quarterly newsletter full of tips and recommendations, please sign up while there.

I’m at that very challenging stage with this one.  I want to keep it raw and spontaneous, but still make sure it has impact.  How much do I clean up so that it has emphasis and dominance?  And how much do I let it stay in its intuitive, raw state?  I find I have to take this stage step-by-step, trying to approach it with fresh eyes every day, before I cover up too much of what I love.

I loved doing #The100DayProject a couple years ago when I made 100 - 4” collages. I loved the discipline and pushing beyond what I thought the limits of my creativity were.  I decided to do the project again this year, but with a less contained approach. 

This year I want to explore rawness in my work, and find out exactly how much rawness I really want.  I want wild, spontaneous freedom, but I also want it cleaned up some so that it has impact. 

Where is that line for me?  I’ve got lots of ideas about how to explore that and have written about it in a new blogpost.  Link in my profile.

I’ve been playing with editing my blindfolded paintings while trying to keep their initial energy as part of my #100dayproject. Working on finding that balance between raw and finished for me. 

If you scroll right you can see the original blindfolded version.  Lots of energy, marks, and intense colors.  Much of that I liked, but it felt a little too chaotic and muddled to me.  I slowly went in with some grays to add contrast to the intense colors.  Happier. Then I needed to open it up a bit to give it some breathing space, so I gradually added some white.  I’m doing these stroke-by-stroke to see just how little I need to edit to make me happy without losing the rawness.

Randomly stitching bits of collage paper together to see where they take me as part of my #100dayproject of staying raw.  I've been grabbing pieces without much thought, stitching them together, slicing them, and mixing them up again.  I was wondering if I could get nice little collages that I Iike by just working randomly the whole way to keep them raw.  The answer is No.  At some point my analytical brain needs to step in to give them some order.  They need some open space or movement or emphasis that doesn’t always occur randomly. 

Now I’m playing with the stitched units to see where they might go.  I'll hand stitch fabric on some of them for a pop of color. And I’m super excited about what happened when I tossed some on top of an unfinished painting. A new serendipitous direction?

I was thrilled to see Bill Park's @williamparkart latest show and hear his artist talk at Laura Vincent Gallery @lvdesignandgallery this month. I’ve taken a number of workshops from Bill, and he really changed the way I paint.  He was the first artist I encountered who is totally absorbed in process over product.  I watched him take one of his large paintings that I was sure was ready to hang on a gallery wall, and put a large stroke of red all across it, just to have something new to respond to.  It was such a great lesson in remaining unattached until you are totally satisfied with a piece.

In one of his workshops, Bill showed a slideshow of working on a large painting for a year, and I think of it every time I start getting into small tweaks.  He took that painting in so many different directions that it is hard to find any of the original elements.  I admire his total dedication to experimentation and remaining present with the work.

My photos aren't the best as I was dodging around a packed room.  I highly recommend catching the show in person if you are in Portland through April. @williamparkart @lvdesignandgallery

One extreme to the other here. The first one I used a very limited palette of Payne’s Grey, Burnt Sienna, slight bit of Cad. Red and white.  In the second one, I used an anything goes palette. I let one color determine what the next should be with no limitations. 

I usually favor a limited palette, but I have to admit that anything goes was a lot of fun!  And produced some juicy little surprises.  Guess I’ll be switching back and forth more often.

As long as I need to test exterior house paint, I might as well make collage papers out of it.  I’m actually pretty excited to try these mucky colors with some pops of color in collages.  It’s funny that even the red from the underlying newspaper really brings them alive.  Coming soon.

Just finished making my newest Artist Mindset journal.  I have so many journals and sketchbooks floating around that I really enjoy having distinct covers for easy identification.

I began the previous one in @cheryltavesart wonderful Artist Mindset program @insightcreativecoaching and this journal is truly one of my treasures.  It’s mainly all journal writing, notes, lists, quotations, centered around mindset.  It’s full of thoughts on the blocks and obstacles to overcome, strategies to work through the blah periods as well as the goals and insights on the deeper purpose of art making to help keep me centered. 

I’ve continued on with Cheryl's ongoing group and am constantly finding new questions to explore or ideas that inspire me to keep me going through the challenging times.  For me mindset has probably been more important than any technique in moving my practice forward.  Do you have ways you explore mindset in your practice?

I was listening to an artist talk by Gage Opdenbrouw @gageopdenbrouw on Winslow Art Center, and he shared these words of wisdom that really struck me.  I never really thought of it as ego that keeps us playing safe, but that is exactly what it is.  How often it nudges us to  make the easier choices to create something we know will give us that ping of success, rather than taking the risks that may very well lead to an ugly mess, but help us grow.

I enjoyed his thoughtful, humble talk.  It’s recorded and you can find it @winslowartcenter

I haven’t done a piece in this series in a while, but needed to jump back in for this commission. I was surprised at how much I forgot!  The basics were all there, but I had to try to figure out how I did the subtleties. Luckily it came back after a little trial and error.  I think I need to keep more thorough notes for long breaks!

I was really happy though to make some new discoveries and see possibilities for new ways of manipulating dark and light areas that I now want to explore. Some distance gave me fresh eyes on these.

My pile of possibilities. I heard a printmaker say she no longer thinks of her bad prints as failures.  Instead she adds them to her pile of possibilities for reworking or collage.

These 5 panels are part of a series that I keep struggling with.  I set out to combine a grid with loose, wild areas.  I was really happy with the first one that worked (in the 2nd picture). But the other 5!  Grid is too pronounced, grid is not pronounced enough, piece doesn't want to integrate, it's too tight, it's too loose…..

When do you throw up your hands, sand it all down, and move on to a new idea?  I felt so much possibility after the first one, so I don’t know if I need to have patience and keep trying or get out the gesso.

I wanted to mix things up some, and a trip to Iceland with my son did exactly that!  Way out of my comfort zone as we hiked on glaciers and explored their interior passages and ice caves. Truly magnificent!

The whole country was fascinating with its dramatic landscapes that are ever shifting. Fjords and volcanoes and glaciers and waterfalls. It’s a lot to take in. 

I broke up all the chilliness with a wonderful day at the Blue Lagoon thermal spa. Perfect counterbalance to climbing through ice caves. 

And the city of Reykjavik was quite charming in its Scandanavian style. Complete with plenty of cozy bakeries. 

We were disappointed not to catch sight of the Northern lights, but there were plenty of other wonders to compensate!

I had a little break between trips and wanted to do some painting, but knew I wouldn’t be able to settle into much in a short period. 

There were a few things I knew I wanted to work on:

1. Being fully present with the piece for as long as I was working on it each session. 

2.  Staying unattached and not trying to create a finished painting. 

3.  Working large and bold. 

I cut a piece of 48x48” paper to work on knowing I wouldn’t think of that as a painting as much as I would canvas or panel. Mainly because I wouldn’t want to frame it. 

I worked following the method I learned in a Steve Aimone workshop—make a mark, then get back, observe, respond to what is there. Every day I rotated it and then responded to the new orientation.  On a couple of the later days, I could see things developing that I liked and thought about keeping the same orientation, but being an exercise in non-attachment, I rotated it anyway. 

I fully enjoyed painting this way. No thoughts towards completion. I think I might next cut it into 24” pieces and do the same with each individual one. Just to keep the juices flowing.
